'''Zelia Ball Page''' (1850-1937) was a freeborn [[African-American]] teacher who spent her career teaching black youths in Missouri, Oklahoma and Tennessee. Her husband was the first head of [[Langston University]] and she was the first matron.

==Early life==
Zelia R. Ball was born on June 21, 1850 in Alexandria, Virginia{{sfn|Dunjee|1937|p=9}}{{#tag:ref|The date shown on Page's tombstone of June 21, 1850{{sfn|Summit View Cemetery|2009}} may be incorrect, as the 1865 census shows her to have been born in 1847.{{sfn|Massachusetts State Census|1865|p=159}} The 1920 census records her as having been born in 1865,{{sfn|U. S. Census|1920|p=7A}} which seems improbable given her graduation from university in 1875.{{snf|''Catalogue of Wilberforce University''|1894|p=27}}|group="Notes"}} to a free black woman who raised her in [[Washington, D. C.]] Her mother worked with the [[Underground Railroad]] and fearing for her daughter's safety, she made an arrangement with [[Peter Parker (physician)|Dr. Peter Parker]] to assist her in taking her child to [[New England]]. Mother and child pretended to be slaves of Parker until they reached the port of New York and were able to make their way to [[Providence, Rhode Island]]. Once in Providence, the school systems were found to be lacking and Ball was sent to be educated in Boston.{{sfn|Majors|1893|pp=50-51}} In 1870, she entered [[Wilberforce University]], graduating with a [[B.S.]] degree in 1875.{{sfn|Majors|1893|p=51}}{{snf|''Catalogue of Wilberforce University''|1894|p=27}}

==Career==
Upon completion of her schooling, Ball returned to Providence{{sfn|Scruggs|1893|p=154}} and applied to become a teacher in Washington, D. C.{{sfn|''The Evening Star''|1875|p=4}} On June 27, 1878, she married [[Inman E. Page]].{{sfn|Scruggs|1893|p=154}} That same year, the couple moved to [[Jefferson City, Missouri]] to begin teaching at the [[Lincoln University (Missouri)|Lincoln Institute]].{{sfn|Holland|1999|p=591}} Page was hired as a science teacher and her husband was initially the assistant principal, though he was promoted to principal in 1880.{{sfn|Scruggs|1893|p=155}}{{sfn|Holland|1999|p=591}}{{sfn|''Reports of the Public Schools''|1881|p=166}} Page taught [[botany]], [[physiology]] and [[zoology]] and in 1885 was appointed as matron.{{sfn|''Reports of the Public Schools''|1884|p=157}}{{sfn|''Reports of the Public Schools''|1886|p=136}} During this time, the couple had three children: [[Zelia N. Breaux|Zelia N.]], Mary and Inman, Jr., who died when he was seven years old.{{sfn|Holland|1999|p=591}} In 1891, Page organized the Union Training School to teach skills to poor black youths and continued teaching at Lincoln for seven more years.{{sfn|Scruggs|1893|p=155}}{{sfn|Holland|1999|p=591}}{{sfn|''The St. Joseph Herald''|1897|p=4}}

In 1898, the couple left Lincoln and moved to [[Langston, Oklahoma|Langston, Oklahoma Territory]], where Inman took up the post as the first head of the [[Langston University|Oklahoma Colored Agricultural and Normal University]].{{sfn|Holland|1999|p=591}} Page was hired as the matron and their daughter Zelia Breaux was hired as the music instructor of the new university.{{sfn|Biennial Report|1908|p=22}} She also served as the Oklahoma officer for the Afro-American Council.{{sfn|''The Appeal''|1899|p=1}} In 1915, the couple left Oklahoma, moving to [[Macon, Missouri]] where Inman became president of the [[Western Baptist College|Colored Baptist College]]. Within three years, they moved to [[Nashville, Tennessee]], where Inman served as president of [[Roger Williams University]] and Page continued teaching.{{sfn|U. S. Census|1920|p=7A}} They briefly returned to Lincoln Institute before moving again to Oklahoma in 1924.{{sfn|Holland|1999|p=591}}{{sfn|White|Bacote|1936|p=238}}

==Death and legacy==
Page died at her daughter Zelia's home in [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]] from heart complications on July 15, 1937.{{sfn|Dunjee|1937|p=9}} In her lifetime, Page's contributions to educating African-American youth were widely recognized.{{sfn|Majors|1893|pp=50-52}}{{sfn|Scruggs|1893|pp=153-155}}{{sfn|Northrop|Gay|Penn|1896|p=107}}

